<!-- inc publications_db -->

 <strong>August 22,  2011</strong><p><i>University Communications, UCI Features</i><p><strong>Bioinformatics Boosters</strong><p><strong>By: Rizza Barnes</strong><br><p>
<P>
<I>
Read the full story below or <A HREF="http://news.uci.edu/features/program-opens-emerging-field-of-bioinformatics-to-students/">view it on the UCI website</A>.
</I>
</P>

<P>
<I>
<A HREF="http://www.flickr.com/photos/brenschool/sets/72157627471250836/">Click here</A> to view photos of the summer program participants. </I>
</P>




<P>
For aspiring computer engineer Anthony Hizon, spending the summer in a biological chemistry lab at UC Irvine&rsquo;s School of Medicine was quite an eye-opener.

<P>
&ldquo;Talking to the Ph.D. students in the lab gave me new ideas about my future,&rdquo; says Hizon, one of seven participants in the newly launched UCI Biomedical Informatics Training Undergraduate Summer Research Program for community college students. &ldquo;I&rsquo;ve learned that bioinformatics is a viable career option for me, and I&rsquo;m now thinking about going to graduate school.&rdquo;

<P>
That sentiment is music to the ears of 
<A HREF="http://www.igb.uci.edu/~pfbaldi/">Pierre Baldi</A>, 
Chancellor&rsquo;s Professor of computer science at the Donald Bren School of Information & Computer Sciences and director of UCI&rsquo;s 
<A HREF="http://www.igb.uci.edu/">Institute for Genomics & Bioinformatics</A>. 
He says the BIT-SR program was created to acquaint students with an emerging field that pairs biology and computer science.

<P>
&ldquo;Our main goal is to see students get excited about science in general,&rdquo; says Baldi, who co-developed BIT-SR with 
<A HREF="http://www.faculty.uci.edu/scripts/ucifacultyprofiles/detaildept.cfm?id=2247">Suzanne Sandmeyer</A>, 
professor of biological chemistry; 
<A HREF="http://www.faculty.uci.edu/scripts/UCIFacultyProfiles/DetailDept.CFM?ID=2473">G. Wesley Hatfield</A>, 
professor emeritus of microbiology & molecular genetics; and Debra Mauzy-Melitz, developmental & cell biology faculty member. &ldquo;Even if just one student each summer decides to take a serious look at pursuing bioinformatics as a career because of this program, I think it will be all the more rewarding for our team.&rdquo;

<P>
Involving both computer and wet lab work, BIT-SR kicked off in June and ended this month with a research symposium. Supported by a five-year, $400,000 National Institutes of Health 
<A HREF="http://today.uci.edu/briefs/2011/07/nb_bitsr_110718.php">grant</A>, 
the program targets first-generation college students from low-income, historically underserved ethnic and racial backgrounds.

<P>
This year&rsquo;s scholars hailed from Rio Hondo, Santa Ana and Santiago Canyon colleges; their research interests included computer science, electrical engineering, pharmacology and microbiology. Each participant worked with a graduate student and faculty adviser for eight weeks and presented findings at the concluding symposium.

<P>
In general, bioinformatics calls for experts in life sciences or computational mathematics, but those cross-trained in both areas are invaluable. Computational science has become particularly important to biological research because high-throughput technologies such as human genome sequencing are so data-intensive.

<P>
To give the BIT-SR scholars firsthand exposure to the experimental workflow of DNA sequencing, the Institute for Genomics & Bioinformatics co-hosted a daylong workshop Aug. 1 with UCI&rsquo;s 
<A HREF="http://ghtf.biochem.uci.edu/">Genomics High-Throughput Facility</A>, 
which performs next-generation sequence analysis for campus investigators.

<P>
At the workshop, students performed the first step of DNA sequencing &mdash; making a genomic library &mdash; and discussed the preparation for and challenges of a career in bioinformatics.

<P>
Hizon stayed on after the BIT-SR program&rsquo;s conclusion to finish his work in Professor Bogi Andersen&rsquo;s 
<A HREF="http://www.biochem.uci.edu/Andersen/people.html">lab</A>, 
where members are exploring potential causes of cancer during organ development. Because of his strong computer science background, Hizon was tasked with building a website to help the researchers more speedily process and evaluate DNA information culled from past studies.

<P>
&ldquo;Currently, they&rsquo;re using Excel to deal with huge data sets involving thousands of genes and 100-plus experiments. It can get very clunky,&rdquo; he explains. &ldquo;My goal is to create a website that lets them generate graphs and models in one or two minutes, so they can quickly analyze the data.&rdquo;

<P>
Hizon, who&rsquo;s headed to Stanford University this fall after attending classes at Rio Hondo and Santiago Canyon colleges, says the cross-training he received this summer &mdash; working in the computer lab and observing in the wet lab &mdash; has allowed for meaningful customization of the website.

<P>
&ldquo;Even though I&rsquo;m working on the computer science side of the project, I needed to get an understanding of what they were doing biologically to determine what kinds of data analysis I could provide,&rdquo; he says. &ldquo;As my mentors gave me information for my computer application to process, I actually understood what the data meant and where it came from.&rdquo;

<P>
His principal mentor, Rachel Herndon, a doctoral student in the Department of Biological Chemistry, says Hizon&rsquo;s addition to her group &ldquo;has been an interesting experience. We&rsquo;re a biology lab, and being able to work full time with a computer scientist has encouraged us to try different approaches to problem solving.&rdquo;

<P>
&ldquo;That&rsquo;s the great thing about UCI&rsquo;s Biomedical Informatics Training Program,&rdquo; she says. &ldquo;It gets computer scientists and biologists talking and collaborating.&rdquo;

<P>
Computer science doctoral student Todd Johnson, who was paired this summer with Christopher Navarro of Santiago Canyon College on a function prediction project, says that serving as a BIT-SR mentor was also valuable in other ways.

<P>
&ldquo;Through the course of my research, I sometimes fall down rabbit holes and go off on a tangent,&rdquo; he says. &ldquo;Not only did Chris produce good work, but having him here helped me stay focused.&rdquo;

<P>
Those BIT-SR scholars not yet bound for a four-year university plan to spread the word about their summer experience when they return to community college.

<P>
&ldquo;I will recommend the program to all my friends when I go back to Rio Hondo,&rdquo; Min Liang says. &ldquo;I feel really lucky to have been a part of this.&rdquo;



<p style="float: right; margin-top: 0em; margin-bottom: 2em; font-style:italic; ">&#8212; Rizza Barnes, Donald Bren School of Information & Computer Sciences
</P>





<br><TITLE>Bioinformatics Boosters</TITLE>

</div>
</blockquote>
</div>
